>
  <article class="prose-dolphin max-w-none">

    <!-- AI Summary -->
    <div class="bg-navy/5 border-l-4 border-gold rounded-r-lg p-4 mb-6">
      <p class="text-sm text-text-light leading-relaxed italic">Dolphin Centrifuge provides expert disc stack centrifuge lubrication guidance for machines operating at 5,000–15,000 RPM. Covers gear drive oil (ISO VG 150–220), spindle bearing lubrication, motor bearing greasing, correct change intervals (2,000–4,000 hours), and common mistakes that cause premature bearing failure.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- Summary Card -->
    <div class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-200 p-6 mb-10 shadow-sm">
      <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed"><strong>Summary:</strong> Disc stack centrifuges run at 5,000&ndash;15,000 RPM depending on model size. At these speeds, inadequate lubrication leads to bearing failure within hours. Correct lubrication protects the spindle bearings, top bearing, gear drive, and motor bearings across <a href="/disc-stack-centrifuge-applications/">all centrifuge applications</a>. This guide is application-general &mdash; always consult the specific machine manual for exact oil types and quantities for your model, as specifications vary.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- Lubrication Points Overview -->
    <h2 id="lubrication-points">Lubrication Points on a Disc Stack Centrifuge</h2>
    <div class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-200 p-6 shadow-sm mb-8">
      <div class="space-y-4 text-text-light">
        <p>A typical horizontal or vertical <a href="/disc-stack-centrifuge-faq/">disc centrifuge</a> has three main lubrication zones, each with different requirements:</p>
        <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-4 mt-4">
          <div class="bg-warm-white rounded-lg p-4 border border-gray-200">
            <h3 class="font-bold text-navy mb-2">Frame / Gear Drive</h3>
            <p class="text-sm">The main oil sump lubricates the gear drive (worm gear or helical gears) and the lower spindle bearing. Splash or forced lubrication depending on model.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-warm-white rounded-lg p-4 border border-gray-200">
            <h3 class="font-bold text-navy mb-2">Top Bearing</h3>
            <p class="text-sm">The upper spindle bearing is typically lubricated separately from the main sump, either by oil bath, forced lubrication, or grease (model-dependent).</p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-warm-white rounded-lg p-4 border border-gray-200">
            <h3 class="font-bold text-navy mb-2">Motor Bearings</h3>
            <p class="text-sm">The electric motor's drive-end and non-drive-end bearings require periodic greasing according to the motor manufacturer's specification.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Main Frame Oil -->
    <h2 id="gear-drive-oil">Main Frame / Gear Drive Oil</h2>
    <div class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-200 p-6 shadow-sm mb-6">
      <div class="space-y-3 text-text-light">
        <p><strong class="text-navy">Function:</strong> Lubricates the worm gear or helical gear drive, the lower spindle bearing, and (on some models) provides cooling for the gear drive assembly. This is the highest-volume lubrication point on the machine.</p>
        <p><strong class="text-navy">Oil type:</strong> Typically a high-quality gear oil meeting ISO VG 150 or ISO VG 220 classification. Some machines specify a synthetic gear oil for extended life and better performance at temperature extremes. Consult the machine manual &mdash; using the wrong viscosity grade is one of the most common lubrication errors.</p>
        <p><strong class="text-navy">Oil quantity:</strong> Fill to the upper mark on the sight glass with the machine stopped and on a level surface. On machines with a sight glass, both the upper and lower marks must be visible &mdash; the oil level should be at or just above the lower mark when the machine is at operating temperature (oil expands at temperature, so cold fill should be at the mid-point).</p>
        <p><strong class="text-navy">Change interval:</strong> The initial oil change should occur after the first 500 hours of operation (break-in period) to remove fine metallic particles from new gear surfaces. Subsequent changes are typically every 2,000&ndash;4,000 operating hours or annually, whichever comes first. In applications with high ambient temperature (above 40&deg;C) or with process fluid contamination risk, reduce the interval to 1,000 hours.</p>
        <p><strong class="text-navy">Checking oil level procedure:</strong></p>
        <ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-1 ml-2">
          <li>Stop the machine and allow the oil to settle for at least 5 minutes.</li>
          <li>Wipe the sight glass clean and read the oil level.</li>
          <li>If below the lower mark, add oil through the fill plug slowly.</li>
          <li>Never overfill above the upper mark &mdash; excess oil causes churning, foaming, and elevated operating temperature.</li>
        </ol>
        <img src="/images/disc-stack-centrifuge-lubrication/Disc-Centrifuge-Oil-Sight-Glass-400.webp" alt="Disc centrifuge oil sight glass showing correct lube oil level" width="400" height="244" loading="lazy" class="rounded-lg w-full mt-4" />
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Top Bearing -->
    <h2 id="top-bearing">Top (Upper Spindle) Bearing</h2>
    <div class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-200 p-6 shadow-sm mb-6">
      <div class="space-y-3 text-text-light">
        <p><strong class="text-navy">Function:</strong> The top bearing supports the upper end of the spindle against lateral forces and maintains spindle concentricity at operating speed. It is the most highly loaded bearing on the machine and the one most likely to fail first if lubrication is neglected.</p>
        <p><strong class="text-navy">Lubrication type:</strong> Top bearings are lubricated in one of three ways depending on machine design:</p>
        <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-1 ml-2">
          <li><strong class="text-navy">Oil bath:</strong> A separate small oil sump around the top bearing. Requires separate oil level monitoring and periodic oil changes.</li>
          <li><strong class="text-navy">Forced oil circulation:</strong> Oil is pumped from the main sump to the top bearing. Correct oil flow rate is essential &mdash; check the oil supply line for blockage if bearing temperature is elevated.</li>
          <li><strong class="text-navy">Grease:</strong> Some smaller models use a sealed grease-packed top bearing. These require regreasing at specified intervals using only the specified grease type and quantity.</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong class="text-navy">Oil type (oil bath models):</strong> Typically a light turbine oil or spindle oil (ISO VG 32 or ISO VG 46). Do not use gear oil in the top bearing sump &mdash; the higher viscosity increases churning resistance and generates heat.</p>
        <p><strong class="text-navy">Change interval:</strong> On oil bath models, change the top bearing oil every 1,000&ndash;2,000 hours or every 6 months. Inspect for contamination (cloudiness, metal particles, process fluid ingress) at every oil level check.</p>
        <p><strong class="text-navy">Grease type (grease-lubricated models):</strong> Use only the specified high-speed bearing grease. High-speed bearings require a grease with the correct base oil viscosity and worked penetration for the application &mdash; a standard lithium grease designed for slow-speed bearings will degrade rapidly in a high-speed centrifuge bearing.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Motor Bearings -->
    <h2 id="motor-bearings">Motor Bearings</h2>
    <div class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-200 p-6 shadow-sm mb-6">
      <div class="space-y-3 text-text-light">
        <p><strong class="text-navy">Function:</strong> Electric motor bearings support the motor shaft and absorb both the motor's own rotating mass and the drive belt tension (in belt-driven models). Motor bearing failure causes motor damage, shaft misalignment, and vibration that propagates into the centrifuge drive system.</p>
        <p><strong class="text-navy">Grease type:</strong> Motor bearings require the grease type specified by the motor manufacturer, not the centrifuge manufacturer. Most standard IEC or NEMA motors specify a lithium-complex grease with an NLGI grade 2 consistency. Do not mix grease types &mdash; incompatible thickener combinations can cause grease softening and loss of film strength.</p>
        <p><strong class="text-navy">Regreasing interval:</strong> Motor bearing regreasing is typically required every 2,000&ndash;4,000 hours depending on motor speed (rpm) and bearing size. Higher-speed motors require more frequent greasing. Refer to the motor nameplate data or manufacturer guide for the exact interval and grease quantity. Overgreasing a motor bearing causes overheating &mdash; the grease purge hole must be opened before regreasing if equipped.</p>
        <p><strong class="text-navy">Access:</strong> Most centrifuge motors have grease nipples (Zerk fittings) accessible through the motor terminal box cover or through dedicated access plugs. Some totally enclosed motors are sealed-for-life and require no grease maintenance.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Common Mistakes -->
    <h2 id="common-mistakes">Common Lubrication Mistakes &amp; Consequences</h2>
    <div class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-200 p-6 shadow-sm mb-8">
      <div class="space-y-4 text-text-light">
        <div class="border-l-4 border-red-400 pl-4">
          <p class="font-bold text-navy">Using the wrong oil grade</p>
          <p>ISO VG 150 vs. ISO VG 220 in the gear drive &mdash; a common substitution error. Too-thin oil does not maintain an adequate lubricant film at operating temperature. Too-thick oil increases churning losses, raises operating temperature, and can prevent adequate flow to the top bearing in forced-circulation systems.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="border-l-4 border-red-400 pl-4">
          <p class="font-bold text-navy">Overfilling the oil sump</p>
          <p>Oil above the maximum mark creates foam from gear churning. Foamy oil does not lubricate effectively, and foam can be drawn into bearing housings. Foam also accelerates oxidation of the oil, shortening its service life.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="border-l-4 border-red-400 pl-4">
          <p class="font-bold text-navy">Extending oil change intervals to save money</p>
          <p>Gear oil oxidizes and degrades with heat and time. Oxidized oil loses its extreme-pressure (EP) additive package and anti-wear protection. Running on degraded oil causes accelerated gear tooth wear that costs far more to repair than the cost of fresh oil. Acid numbers rise in aged oil, causing corrosive attack on bearing and gear surfaces.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="border-l-4 border-red-400 pl-4">
          <p class="font-bold text-navy">Ignoring contaminated oil</p>
          <p>If the sump oil appears milky or contains metallic particles, changing the oil alone is insufficient. Milky oil indicates water contamination (from a failed spindle neck seal or process fluid ingress) &mdash; the source must be found and repaired or the new oil will be contaminated again within days. Metal particles indicate active gear or bearing wear that will continue until the root cause is corrected.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="border-l-4 border-red-400 pl-4">
          <p class="font-bold text-navy">Overgreasing motor bearings</p>
          <p>Adding too much grease to a motor bearing creates heat from churning and can rupture bearing seals, allowing grease to enter the motor windings. Follow the specified grease quantity precisely &mdash; typically measured in grams, not pump strokes.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Oil Change Procedure -->
    <h2 id="oil-change-procedure">Main Sump Oil Change Procedure</h2>
    <div class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-200 p-6 shadow-sm mb-8">
      <img src="/images/disc-stack-centrifuge-lubrication/Disc-Centrifuge-Lube-Lubricant-Draining-400.webp" alt="Disc centrifuge lubricant draining procedure" width="400" height="244" loading="lazy" class="rounded-lg w-full mb-4" />
      <ol class="space-y-3 text-text-light list-decimal list-inside ml-2">
        <li><strong class="text-navy">Run the machine to operating temperature before draining.</strong> Warm oil flows more completely from the sump, removing more contaminants. Never drain cold oil &mdash; it leaves too much residue behind.</li>
        <li><strong class="text-navy">Stop the machine and lock out / tag out the electrical supply.</strong> Allow the spindle to come to a complete stop.</li>
        <li><strong class="text-navy">Place a drain pan under the drain plug.</strong> Open the drain plug and allow the oil to drain completely. On machines with a magnetic drain plug, inspect the plug for accumulated metallic particles and note the amount &mdash; more particles than last time indicates a developing wear problem.</li>
        <li><strong class="text-navy">Flush the sump if contamination was found.</strong> Fill with a small quantity of flushing oil or fresh gear oil, close the drain, run the machine briefly (5 minutes) at operating speed with no process load, then drain again.</li>
        <li><strong class="text-navy">Install the drain plug and fill with fresh oil</strong> to the midpoint of the sight glass. Check the level after a 5-minute run to correct for oil distribution throughout the system.</li>
        <li><strong class="text-navy">Record the oil change</strong> in the machine maintenance log including date, hours, oil brand and grade, quantity, and any observations about the drained oil condition.</li>
      </ol>
    </div>

    <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mb-6">For questions about oil specifications for a specific machine model, or to order replacement bearings, contact Dolphin Centrifuge at <a href="tel:+12485222573">(248) 522-2573</a> or <a href="mailto:sales@dolphincentrifuge.com">sales@dolphincentrifuge.com</a>. Refer to our <a href="/disc-stack-centrifuge-mechanical-issues-fixes/">mechanical troubleshooting guide</a> if you are experiencing bearing or gear issues. See also our <a href="/industrial-disc-centrifuge-repair/">centrifuge repair services</a> for complete drive train rebuilds.</p>

    <!-- FAQ -->
    <div id="faq" class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-100 shadow-sm p-6 md:p-8 mt-10 mb-6">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-navy mb-6">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="space-y-6">
        <div>
          <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-navy mb-2">What type of oil is used in a disc stack centrifuge?</h3>
          <p class="text-text-light text-sm">Disc stack centrifuges typically require an ISO VG 68 or VG 100 mineral gear oil for the main sump and a separate oil or grease for spindle bearings. Alfa Laval specifies particular grades for each model — using the wrong viscosity causes overheating, premature bearing wear, and gear damage. Always consult the machine manual or the manufacturer for the correct specification.</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-navy mb-2">How often should disc centrifuge oil be changed?</h3>
          <p class="text-text-light text-sm">Main sump oil should typically be changed every 2,000–4,000 operating hours, or at least annually — whichever comes first. The first oil change should be done early (500 hours) on new or rebuilt machines to flush break-in debris. Refer to your model's maintenance manual for exact intervals.</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-navy mb-2">What happens if a disc centrifuge is run without enough oil?</h3>
          <p class="text-text-light text-sm">Running with insufficient lubricant causes rapid bearing and gear overheating, leading to bearing failure, gear damage, and potentially complete machine failure. Oil level should be checked at every startup — the sight glass should read at midpoint when the machine is at rest.</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-navy mb-2">Can I use synthetic oil in a disc stack centrifuge?</h3>
          <p class="text-text-light text-sm">Synthetic gear oils can be used if they meet the viscosity grade and additive specifications required by the manufacturer. Synthetics offer better thermal stability and longer service intervals than mineral oils. Always confirm seal compatibility and follow the manufacturer's guidance on drain intervals for synthetic lubricants.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Related Articles -->
    <div class="mt-10">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-navy mb-4">Related Articles</h2>
      <div class="grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
        <a href="/disc-stack-centrifuge-vibration/" class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-200 p-4 shadow-sm hover:border-gold transition-colors no-underline">
